The stability performance is vital for fluorescence sensor. Therefore, the fluorescence intensity of N-CDs in different salt concentrations and pH values were recorded to explore the stability of N-CDs. Similar with other CDs, slight fluorescence changes of N-CDs can be found in the range of NaCl concentration from 0 to 2 M (

                           Figure S2a

                        ). It indicated that N-CDs-based fluorescence sensing can be performed without the interference of high salt concentration environments. The pH effect on the N-CDs was also investigated (

                           Figure S2b

                        ). The fluorescence intensity of the N-CDs was steady in pH value range of the 3–10, whereas 23 % of intensity decrease appears at pH value of 12. Thus, the fluorescence of N-CDs is stable and suitable for fabricating sensor.

Furthermore, the fluorescence of N-CDs/Hg2+ can be restored after adding with GSH, whereas no fluorescence enhancement can be observed in N-CDs/Fe3+ systems (
Figure S3
). It indicated that the recognition between Hg2+ and Fe3+ can be performed, and the N-CDs/Hg2+ system is suitable to detect GSH via an off–on method. In order to examine the effect of amino acids on the fluorescence of N-CDs, 17 kinds of amino acids were added into N-CDs solutions. Figure S4 showed that amino acids have little effect on the fluorescence intensity of N-CDs. The fluorescence intensity of N-CDs/Hg2+ system was recovered obviously after the addition of GSH and Cys (
Figure S5
), because of the combination between thiol and Hg2+. These results indicated that these N-CDs/Hg2+ are suitable for sensing thiols.

The UV–vis absorption spectra of N-CDs were tested under Hg2+ and Fe3+ in concentrations of 300 μM, respectively. No significant changes can be observed in the UV absorption peaks of N-CDs (

                           Figure S6

                        a), and the results indicated that it excluded static quenching [27]. After adding EDTA, the fluorescence of N-CDs recovered (

                           Figure S6

                        b), which proved that there is coordination between N-CDs and Hg2+ or Fe3+. Furthermore, the zeta potential of N-CDs solution is −9.3 mV. After adding Hg2+ and Fe3+, the zeta potential of N-CDs/Hg2+ and N-CDs/Fe3+ mixed solution was 21 mV and 12.7 mV respectively (

                           Figure S7

                        ). Using single exponential function It = I0 e-kt fitting, the average fluorescence lifetimes of N-CDs, N-CDs/Hg2+, N-CDs/Fe3+ and N-CDs/Hg2+ with GSH addition were 3.12 ns, 2.59 ns, 2.66 ns and 2.93 ns, respectively (

                           Table S1

                        ). After adding Hg2+ and Fe3+, the fluorescence lifetime decreased. When GSH was added to the N-CDs/Hg2+ system, the fluorescence lifetime was restored to 2.93 ns. The results suggested that the fluorescence quenching effect of Hg2+ and Fe3+ on N-CDs maybe attributed to efficient electron transfer. The fluorescence recovery of N-CDs was ascribed to the effective blocking of electron transfer, resulting in fluorescence recovery [27]. As the existence of hydroxyl and amino groups in N-CDs, Hg2+ and Fe3+ coordinated with N-CDs and affected the surface state of N-CDs via electron transfer, which resulted in fluorescence quenching [28–31]. The coordination of N-CDs with Hg2+ and Fe3+ showed good selectivity for Hg2+ and Fe3+. The coordination and binding capacity of GSH toward Hg2+ was greater than that of CDs [32,33]. Moreover, in the absence of sulfhydryl amino acids, Hg2+ as a soft acid had a certain affinity to histidine (

                           Figure S5

                        ) 
                        [34]. It was the reason why the slight recovery of fluorescence by the addition of histidine to the N-CDs/Hg2+ system. After the addition of GSH, the GSH thiol group binded with Hg2+, resulting in the block of electron transfer and the recovery of the fluorescence response of N-CDs (Scheme 1
                        ). However, the coordinative binding ability between Fe3+ and GSH was low, so the fluorescence was not recovered (
                        Scheme 1
                        ). Therefore, according to the difference between Hg2+ and Fe3+ with GSH adding, the logical gates and identification for Hg2+ and Fe3+ were successfully performed.

We selected river water as real samples to evaluate the feasibility of the method for detecting Hg2+. The Hg2+ recovery rate was in the range of 104.6–109.6%, and the relative standard deviation was in the range of 0.42–3.29% (
                        Table 1

                        ). The above results indicated that N-CDs-based fluorescent probes can be used to detect Hg2+ in real samples.
